    "attributes": {
        "action": "Ban unconditional offers for entrance to university",
        "additional_details": "The number of unconditional offers for entrance to university made to 18 year olds in England, Wales and N.I. is exploding:\r\n\r\n2013      3,000\r\n2014    12,100\r\n2015    23,400\r\n2016    36,800\r\n2017    51,600\r\n\r\nUCAS recorded one in six applicants receiving one or more unconditional offers in 2017.\r\n\r\nSuch offers remove the incentive for pupils to work, leading to lower attainment at A Level, as UCAS' own research has demonstrated: see pages 18-9 of https://www.ucas.com/file/71796/download?token=D4uuSzur.",
        "background": "Universities have embarked on a race to the bottom in admissions standards in a now liberalised marketplace. To benefit society, the free market needs a framework of rules within which to operate. The government should legislate to prohibit this harmful practice, which is damaging pupil attainment.",
